Dataset

The dataset is the nassCDS dataset, from the package DAAG. It contains data about traffic incidents, recorded from 1997 to 2002, where at least one vehicle was towed and there was harm to people or property. This data is sampled by the NASS (Nationat Automotive Sampling System), mantained by a US government agency, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA).

The dataset has dimensions 26217, 15, with 26217 observations and 15 columns. The columns are:

  • dvcat: ordered factor containing the estimated impact speed, with levels 1-9 km/h, 10-24, 25-39, 40-54, 55+;

  • dead: whether the person is dead or alive;

  • weight: observation weight of the entry: this dataset is a summary of a much bigger dataset with ~12 million entries. To model the actual dataset, we have to consider the weight of each observation;

  • airbag: factor with levels none and airbag, representing whether the vehicle had an airbag;

  • seatbelt: factor with levels none and belted, representing whether the person had their seatbelt on;

  • frontal: numeric value, 1 for frontal impact, 0 for not

  • sex: factor with levels f and m, for the sex of the person

  • ageOFocc: numerical age in years of the occupant

  • yearacc: year of the accident

  • yearVeh: year of fabrication of the vehicle

  • abcat: factor describing whether or not at least one airbag deployed. Levels are deploy, nodeploy and unavail

  • occRole: factor describing the position of the occupant: driver or pass

  • deploy: numeric vector: 0 if an airbag was unavailable or did not deploy; 1 if one or more bags deployed.

  • injSeverity: numeric vector describing gravity of injuries: 0:none, 1:possible injury, 2:no incapacity, 3:incapacity, 4:killed; 5:unknown, 6:prior death

  • caseid: id of the case

All in all, we have:

  • 3 numerical but not continuous predictors: dvcat, ageOFocc and yearveh;

  • 6 binary predictors: airbag, deploy, seatbelt, sex, frontal and occRole;

  • injSeverity and dead as possible responses

Severity of injuries

Questions we can look at

We can use two different responses: dead and injSev.Relative to these variables, we want to look at the following questions:

  • Which factors make cars safer?

  • There are 2 major safety measures: airbags and seatbelts. How much do these help? Is there synergy between them?

  • How do those safety measures interact with other factors, such as the speed of impact or the position and sex of the occupant?

  • Are cars built later safer?

Preprocessing

Before modeling the data, there are a few problems we need to look at:

  • There are 3 variables that model the action of airbags. Since they are very strongly correlated, we cannot use more than one as predictor

  • We need to convert all the categorical variables to numeric values

  • The caseid is useless

  • Injury severity 5 (unknown) and 6 (prior death) are useless to us, so we need to delete data with these levels of injury

  • We decided to add a feature of the vehicle age, calculated as yearacc-yearVeh

  • We need to round the weights of observations

pdata<-data.frame(data)
pdata$vehage<-pdata$yearacc-pdata$yearVeh
pdata$weight<-round(pdata$weight)
pdata<-pdata[pdata$weight>0,]
pdata<-subset(pdata,select=-c(caseid,abcat))

The airbag variables

To sum them up:

  • deploy=1 if the airbag deployed (abcat=deploy), 0 if it didnt (abcat=nodeploy or unavail)

  • airbag=1 if the vehicle had an airbag(abcat= deploy or nodeploy), 0 if it didnt (abcat=unavail)

We decided to use the airbag variable. Deploy might be influenced by things like the speed of impact or other factors of the incident, while airbag depends only on the vehicle.

Categorical variables

  • We set dead=1 when the occupant died

  • seatbelt=1 when belted

  • sex=1 when f

  • occRole=1 when driver

Correlations between variables

Before modeling injSeverity, we took a look at how the variables are related to each other.

To find dependencies between them, we use Cramers V:

  • Using a chi-square test of independence would be useless, since our dataset is very large, which makes p-values very small.

The airbag vs injury severity problem

A possible explanation for the seeming uselessness of airbags could be the following: in many incidents the occupant was not wearing their seatbelt. It could be that not wearing a seatbelt might make the airbag dangerous.

We create a table with the mean injuries depending on airbag and seatbelt:

count.tab<-xtabs(weight~airbag+seatbelt,data=data)
tab<-xtabs(injSeverity*weight~airbag+seatbelt,data=data)

## airbag        none    belted
##   none   1.4451376 0.7466525

So airbags do seem to help, but very little

To clearly separate the effects of airbags and seatbelts, we create 3 variables that model the 4 possible situations in terms of airbags and seatbelts:

  • both airbag and seatbelt

  • only the seatbelt

  • only the airbag

pdata$beltedab <- pdata$airbag * pdata$seatbelt
pdata$onlyseatbelt=pdata$seatbelt*(1-pdata$airbag)
pdata$onlyairbag=pdata$airbag*(1-pdata$seatbelt)

We now model the injury severity as a response of the other variables.

Modeling injSeverity

Ordered logistic regression models

Ordered logistic regression is used to model categorical variables where the categories have a natural order, making it a good fit for modeling injSeverity.

Given a categorical variable with (ordered) levels 1,,J, for \(j=1,...,J-1\), we define \[ log\frac{P(Y\leq j)}{P(Y > j)}=logit(P(Y\leq j)) \]

And we model it as \[ logit(P(Y\leq j))=\beta_j+\sum_{i=1}^p \eta_i x_i \]

There is an intercept for each cutoff between levels, and it represents the point where we cut the latent variable to create the different levels.

Useful functions

We now define some useful R functions:

Compute p values of parameters

polr models do not include p values by default, so we create a function to compute and print them:

compute_p<-function(m){
  ctable <- coef(summary(m))
  p <- pt(abs(ctable[, "t value"]),m$df.residual, lower.tail = FALSE) * 2
  ctable <- cbind(ctable, "p value" = p)
  print(ctable)
}

Deviance tests

The deviance test is used to test whether a certain subset of parameters is useful

test_deviance<-function(full.m,reduced.m){
  full_dev<-deviance(full.m)
  reduced_dev<-deviance(reduced.m)
  deg<-reduced.m$df.residual-full.m$df.residual
  print(pchisq(reduced_dev-full_dev,deg,lower.tail=FALSE))
}

Evaluate model

We use this function to compute the confusion matrix for multi classification models and calculate statistics describing their performance on a test set.

The statistics were most interested in are:

  • The accuracy

  • Cohens kappa statistic, a measure of the concordance between the truth and the predictions that takes into account the amount of concordance thats due to randomness

  • The balanced accuracy, the average of the recall obtained on each class

ev.model<-function(m,data){
  preds<-predict(m,data,type='class')
  data$preds<-preds
  conf.mat<-conf_mat(data,injSevFactor,preds,case_weights=weight)
  print(summary(conf.mat))
  autoplot(conf.mat,type='heatmap')
}

Verifying the proportional odds assumption

The ordered logistic regression model assumes that the coefficients that describe the relationship between each division of the categories are the same.

We can verify this assumption graphically by creating a table with the odds of being at least in a certain category, divided by each predictor, and plotting them.

duptimes<-pdata$weight

idx<-rep(1:nrow(pdata),duptimes)

unfolded.data <- pdata[idx,]   # 'Unfolding' the dataset weights


sf <- function(y) {   # Function that computes odds of at least being in a certain category
  c('Y>=1' = qlogis(mean(y >= 1)),
    'Y>=2' = qlogis(mean(y >= 2)),
    'Y>=3' = qlogis(mean(y >= 3)),
    'Y>=4' = qlogis(mean(y >= 4)),
    'Y>=5' = qlogis(mean(y >= 5)))
}

Best subset model

We now search for the best subset using the AIC.

First we use a greedy algorithm to subtract the predictors in order of importance, then search for the best partial model based on the performance on a hold out validation set.

sample <- sample.split(train.data$weight, SplitRatio = 0.7)
train.tr  <- subset(pdata, sample == TRUE)
train.v   <- subset(pdata, sample == FALSE)

We use the stepAIC function, using \(k=ln(N)\) (we use the BIC)

empty.m<-polr(injSevFactor~+1,data=train.tr,weights=weight)
stepAIC(empty.m,scope=injSevFactor~onlyseatbelt+onlyairbag+beltedab+dvcat+sex+ageOFocc+occRole+frontal+vehage,direction='forward',k=log(sum(train.tr$weight)))

Adding interactions

There are 36 possible interactions between the predictors. To narrow them and make the fitting easier, we look at the following possible interactions:

  • between dvcat and onlyairbag/onlyseatbelt/beltedab: do these safety measures work better/worse at higher speeds?

  • between sex and onlyairbag/onlyseatbelt/beltedab: do they work better for men or women?

  • between frontal and onlyairbag/onlyseatbelt/beltedab: do they help more in frontal impacts?

sex

sex.m<-polr(injSevFactor~sex*(onlyseatbelt+onlyairbag+beltedab)+dvcat+occRole+frontal+ageOFocc+vehage,data=train.data,weights=weight,Hess=TRUE)

Sex does seem to interact with safety measures: it seems that they work worse for women.

Multinomial logistic regression

We now try a multinomial logistic regression model.

By doing this, we gain the ability to use different coefficients for the relationships between different classes, but we lose the information that the target variables levels are ordered.

Subset selection with Lasso

We use lasso regression perform variable selection:

train.x<-as.matrix(subset(train.data,select=-c(weight,dead,airbag,seatbelt,yearacc,yearVeh,deploy,injSeverity,injSevFactor)))
train.y<-train.data$injSevFactor
test.x<-as.matrix(subset(test.data,select=-c(weight,dead,airbag,seatbelt,yearacc,yearVeh,deploy,injSeverity,injSevFactor)))
test.y<-test.data$injSevFactor

These numbers represent the multiplicative increase in the odds of an incident resulting in a worse injury.

Some observations:

  • As we hypothesized, airbags on their own arent very useful, and might actually be harmful

  • For each 10 km/h of speed, the odds increase by 1.7908477!

  • Women tend to have worse outcomes than men

  • For each 10 extra years of age of the occupant or the vehicle, the odds of worse injuries increase by 1.1046221

To try and simplify the problem, we turn injury severity into a binary variable, with value 1 in cases of incapacity or killed and zero otherwise.

Since models only seem to gain around 3% accuracy compared to the null model, we tried simpifying the problem: instead of predicting the level of injury, we define a binary variable with value 1 in cases of incapacity or death, and 0 otherwise.

pdata$severe<-as.numeric(pdata$injSeverity>=3)

Modeling the severe variable

This is now a binary classification problem.

Useful functions

Accuracy

acc.log<-function(m,data){
  target<-data$severe
  pred<-predict(m,newdata=data, type="response") > 0.5
  success<-data[target==pred,]
  sum(success$weight)/sum(data$weight)
}

Draw ROC curve and get AUC

roc.auc<-function(m,data,make.plot=FALSE){
  target<-data$severe
  pred<-predict(m,newdata=data, type="response")
  weights<-data$weight
  my.roc<-WeightedROC(pred,target,weights)
  print(WeightedAUC(my.roc))
  if (make.plot==TRUE){
    gg<-ggplot()+geom_path(aes(FPR,TPR),data=my.roc)+coord_equal()
    gg
  }
  
}

This model can be interpreted in order to understand the influence of each predictor on the final result. The biggest coefficient is the dvcat which is positive, which means that the higher the speed of the accidents the more probable is to get seriously hurt/get dead. On the other hand, the other relevant coefficients are beltedab and onlyseatbelt which have negative coefficients: this means that using a seatbelt reduces the gravity of the wounds of an accident, and the activation of an airbag together with the presence of a seatbelt reduces the gravity of the accident by almost twice the value. It is interesting to note that if the airbag activates but the passenger does not wear a seatbelt the effect is that there is a higher probability of severe injury. All other factors have an effect that can be ignored, or such that the regularization has penalized them up to making them 0. Thus we can conclude that this regularized model (as well as the other models) confirms the initial conclusions we got from studying the correlations. After this whole analysis we can conclude that the main variable influencing the severity of an injury is the speed at which the accidents happened, followed in minor measure by the activation of seatbelt and/or airbag.

Discriminant Analysis methods

Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)

Although we got quite good results with regularized models, we will also try other models, like LDA and QDA. These models have a theoretical problem because our dataset has almost only binary variables, which are not really fit to this model. LDA is more suited for continuous predictors.

lda_model<-lda(severe~dvcat+frontal+sex+ageOFocc+vehage+onlyairbag+onlyseatbelt+beltedab+occRole, data=train.data, weights=train.data$weight)

lda_model.pred<-predict(lda_model, test.data, weights=test.data$weight)
lda_model.post<-lda_model.pred$posterior
lda_model.class<-lda_model.pred$class

mean(lda_model.class!=test.data$severe)*100
## [1] 28.37082

At first we look for the coefficients returned by the model

coef(lda_model)
##                      LD1
## dvcat         0.06770665
## frontal      -0.35100585
## sex           0.36236311

## onlyairbag   -0.22928480
## onlyseatbelt -1.04681659
## beltedab     -1.27082431
## occRole       0.11057116

As seen in the majority of the models, the most relevant factors, those with the highest coefficients, are the accidents speed, the presence of the seatbelt and the activation of the airbag, but only if the injured person was wearing a seatbelt in the accident.

We now test various thresholds to see whether it can be reached a better result

#threshold=0.4

Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)

QDA differs from LDA in the fact that all predictors have different variances, but it suffers from the same problem of Linear Discriminant Analysis.

qda_model

We see that in our setting the QDA model gives us worse results than simple LDA. From a general point of view, regularized models proved to be the best solution for this specific problem due to the risk of overfitting, although also the Discriminant Analysis methods turned out to be quite good even if they are generally better performing in multiclass problems. The Elastic Net regression was not excessively better than simple Ridge or Lasso regression since these two already had similar performances. All models give out the same result that the most significative predictor is the dvcat, i.e.the speed at which the accidents happen, and as already seen in our previous analysis the airbag becomes effective almost only in presence of the seatbelt, turning out to be quite dangerous if not cohadiuvated.

This may be due to their smaller physique, that increases the gap with the seatbelt and the airbagand creates a higher risk of damage due to airbag inflation.

Conclusions

We analyzed the nassCDS dataset of US traffic accidents.

Weve found that:

  • There is a large random component in the severity of injuries in accidents, which makes them hard to predict accurately

  • The most important factor is the impact speed

  • Airbags are mostly useless on their own, and even dangerous at low speeds. They must be used together with seatbelts

  • Safety measures (airbags and seatbelts) work worse for women (but they still reduce risk)

  • Drivers are safer than passengers
